<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Notes CRS Report on Wheat Exports, MFN Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Notes CRS Report on Wheat Exports, MFN Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2505211594 Beijing XINHUA in English 2051 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2505211594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. Farm Income To Decline if China Stops Buying" -- </F>
XINHUA headline] 
  [Text] Washington, May 25 (XINHUA) -- U.S. farm income will 
decline by nearly 100 million U.S. dollars a year if China, the 
buyer of one-fifth of American wheat exports, stops doing so, a 
congressional report said today. 
  By 1996, the Congressional Research Service (CRS) said, the 
U.S. would experience export losses of 250 million bushels of 
wheat if China retaliates the withdrawal of its most favored 
nation (MFN) trade status. 
  The resulting weaker demand and larger U.S. stocks will 
depress U.S. wheat prices by about 15 cents per bushel by 1996, 
the report said. 
  President Clinton will decide by June 3 whether to renew 
China's MFN status, which makes China, like most other nations 
in the world, enjoy the lowest possible tariffs in its exports 
to the U.S.. 
  "The psychological effect of losing a major foreign wheat 
market might tend to push U.S. prices down even further in the 
future," the CRS said in its report to the House Committee on 
Agriculture. 
  The CRS stressed, meanwhile, that China will continue to be 
"a significant buyer" of American wheat assuming that China's 
MFN status will be extended. 
  China became a major U.S. farm export market in 1987, when 
it 
broke into the ranks of the top 20 importers of farm products. 
Wheat has amounted to between 60 and 92 percent of China's farm 
imports from the U.S.. 
  Since 1989, however, China's rank in wheat imports has 
slipped, with the purchase of 376 million dollars of U.S. wheat 
last year, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture. 
  According to the department, the Chinese typically prefer to 
buy high quality, high protein wheats, such as hard red spring 
or winter wheat, which they mill for flour for bread and other 
baked goods. 
  "Other wheat exporting countries," the report said, "hold 
enough wheat stocks to fill China's lost supplies from the U.S., 
should China choose to reject U.S. wheat exports altogether" in 
the next three years. 
  In addition to wheat, China purchases a broad array of U.S. 
farm products, including grains, soybeans, cotton, livestock, 
horticultural products and even wine and tobacco. 
  Wheat accounted for half of the value of U.S. exports to 
China in 1992. A major proportion of U.S. wheat exports to 
China have been subsidized by the U.S. Government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-51278 </DOCNO>
