<H3> <TI>   Yugoslavia Rules Out Joining NATO Peace Partnership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yugoslavia Rules Out Joining NATO Peace Partnership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2505204294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1608 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2505204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 25 (XINHUA) -- The Yugoslav Federal 
Republic today ruled out the possibility of Joining the NATO 
proposed Partnership for Peace program. 
  Speaking at a press conference here today, Radoje Kontic, 
the 
prime minister of the Federal Republic, said that his country 
maintains a foreign policy of independence, and will not seek 
any tie with NATO. 
  He also said that the country will not join any other 
military alliance either. 
  This is the first time the government of the Yugoslav 
Federal 
Republic rules out the possibility of joining the NATO 
Partnership for Peace program. 
  Kontic also said that his government supports all peace 
proposals that treat the three warring sides in Bosnia on an 
equal foot, and respect the interests of the people of all sides. 
  He also said that any peace proposal should include the 
lifting, or at least the reducing, of the current economic 
sanctions against his country. 
  "To continue maintaining the sanctions is to encourage the 
Muslims to continue the war," he said, adding that the sanctions 
are against humanitarian principles and are damaging the image 
of the United Nations. 
  The sanctions are not only bringing tremendous losses to the 
economy of Yugoslavia, but also to its neighboring countries, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

