<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Border Trade With Nepal Flourishes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Border Trade With Nepal Flourishes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2505110594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0723 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2505110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lhasa, May 25 (XINHUA) -- The Zham trading post in 
Tibet, the only channel for trade between China and Nepal, has 
been bustling in the past few years, as the annual trade value 
on the Sino-Nepalese border hit 300 million yuan (about 35 
million U.S. dollars) last year. 
  Located at the foot of the southern Himalayas, Zham has 
served as a political, economic and cultural passageway between 
China and Nepal since the Sino-Nepalese highway opened in 1965. 
However, the annual border trade volume was worth only seven 
million yuan (800,000 U.S. dollars) in 1979. 
  Along with China's reform and open policy, Zham has become 
prosperous as hotels, power stations, post offices, banks, and 
industry and commerce offices have sprung up and more business 
people have been flocking there. 
  Now the port boasts 3,000 residents, most of whom are 
businessmen from the Tibet Autonomous Region and other Chinese 
provinces, and Nepal. 
  According to local officials, ten percent of the local trade 
volume is done in U.S. dollars, 30 percent in Nepalese currency 
and 50 percent in renminbi. The rest is barter trade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

