<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangdong Secretary Ends Visit To Germany, Denmark </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guangdong Secretary Ends Visit To Germany, Denmark </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2605114494 Guangzhou Guangdong People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 0400 GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2605114494 </F>
<F P=104>  Guangzhou Guangdong People's Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] After successfully winding up an official visit to 
Germany and Denmark, Xie Fei, CPC Central Committee Political 
Bureau member and Guangdong Provincial CPC Committee secretary, 
returned to Guangzhou yesterday evening. 
  In Germany, Xie Fei and his entourage held extensive talks 
with friends in German industrial, commercial, and banking 
circles and briefed German friends on Guangdong's economic 
growth, investment environment, and projects open to foreign 
investment. The two sides also held conscientious discussions 
on ways and means of expanding bilateral cooperation and 
exchanges. 
  In order to acquire a better understanding of the German 
economic, cultural, and environmental protection situations, Xie 
Fei and his entourage inspected Frankfort Airport, which is 
currently undergoing extension; travelled on a high-speed 
railroad in a high-speed special train made by Germany's Siemens 
Company; and visited a farm in Bavaria, where they also called 
on the farm owner. 
  During their two-day stay in Denmark, the Guangdong 
provincial economic investigation delegation led by Xie Fei held 
separate talks with Denmark's ministers of agriculture and 
fisheries and foreign affairs and conscientiously conducted 
investigations into Denmark's agricultural production, farm 
products processing, and agricultural management structure. 
  In their talks with people of all walks of life in Germany 
and Denmark, Xie Fei and his entourage fully publicized the 
excellent opportunities in and good prospects for 
Guangdong-Germany and Guangdong-Denmark economic and 
technological cooperation; expressed the hope that both sides 
would make continued efforts to further bilateral cooperation 
and exchanges; and discussed and agreed on with Germany and 
Denmark specific forms of bilateral cooperation as well as a 
number of joint-venture projects. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

