<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shenzhen Builds Own Power Industry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shenzhen Builds Own Power Industry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2705024194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0133 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2705024194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shenzhen, May 26 (XINHUA) -- Shenzhen, a special 
economic zone in south China's Guangdong Province, has built 
several power plants with a total generating capacity of more 
than two million kw in the past six years. 
  Since the city was approved as a special economic zone in 
1980, the booming economy and growing population of the city 
have required an expanding power supply. 
  In China, almost all large power plants were financed by the 
state in the past. But the city decided in 1987 to build power 
plants by itself, setting many favorable policies to encourage 
overseas and local investors. 
  At present, a thermal power plant with a generating capacity 
of 1.8 million kw is under construction. According to its power 
development program, the city will construct two more large 
power plants in the near future. 
  The program calls for the total generating capacity of the 
city's power plants to reach 6.35 million kw by the end of this 
century, to cover most of the city's power needs. 

</TEXT>

