Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tourists Warned About `High Risk' Spots in Mainland </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tourists Warned About `High Risk' Spots in Mainland </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2605164394 Taipei CNA in English 1250 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2605164394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 26 (CNA) -- Although the Taipei 
Association of Travel Agents lifted a ban on group travel to 
Mainland China Wednesday, the ROC [Republic of China] Consumers 
Foundation warned the public to avoid traveling to "high risk" 
places in the mainland. 
  Foundation Secretary-General Chiang Chih-chun said that 
personal safety is not the only factor to be considered in 
traveling to the mainland. He said that the public may have no 
way to file complaints if there is trouble because of the lack 
of agreement on travel safety and compensation between the two 
sides of the Taiwan Strait. 
  He noted that the bureau of tourism and the Taipei 
Association of Travel Agents have published a list of "high 
risk" locations in the mainland and travelers should use the 
list as a reference. 
  The travel agents lifted the self-imposed ban Wednesday [25 
May] after losing more than NT [New Taiwan] $700 million 
(U.S.$26 million), the officials said. The ban was imposed in 
response to the March 31 robbery and murder of 24 Taiwan 
tourists in Qiandao Lake in Zhejiang Province. 
  The association officials said that although the ban, 
imposed 
on May 1, was lifted, they did not expect group travel to the 
mainland to resume for a few months. 
  The association warned travel agencies to avoid high-risk 
areas such as Qiandao Lake, Zhangjiajie in Hunan Province, Tibet 
and Jiouzaigou in Sichuan Province. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

