<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Calls For Solidarity To Speed Up Reforms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Calls For Solidarity To Speed Up Reforms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2605171394 Taipei CNA in English 1326 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2605171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 26 (CNA) -- President Li Teng-hui on 
Thursday [26 May] called for the government and public to close 
ranks so as to accomplish the goals of national development. 
  Li made the call before concluding his five-day presence at 
the session of the National Assembly in which he solicited 
opinions from assembly members on national-affairs issues. 
  He said that Taiwan, behind the joint effort of the 
government and people, has built up its status in the 
international community behind the strength of its economy, but 
that to keep that status, it needs to face up to sharper 
international competition economically and the threat by Beijing 
to isolate it politically. 
  He said that regardless of party affiliation or birthplace, 
Taiwan citizens "should demonstrate the spirit of solidarity to 
pool together our strength and wisdom so as to accomplish 
political reforms, expand our diplomatic arena and increase our 
economic strength," President Li said. 
  During the past five days, 302 out of the 314 National 
Assembly members voiced their concerns on national affairs, 
especially regarding constitutional reforms, the national 
identity, cross- strait relations, foreign operations, judicial 
and educational reforms, and agricultural development. 
  The National Assembly began its three-month special session 
on May 2 to consider proposed amendments to the constitution and 
the nominations by Li of grand justices and the head of the 
Judicial Yuan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

